  "prompt": "Is banning commercial surrogacy an answer to the exploitation of the surrogates.?",
  "response": "This is a complex issue with valid arguments on different sides. Here's a balanced perspective:\n\nArguments for Banning Commercial Surrogacy:\n1. Prevents exploitation of economically vulnerable women\n2. Reduces potential human trafficking risks\n3. Protects women from potential health risks\n4. Prevents commodification of human reproduction\n5. Reduces potential reproductive tourism\n\nArguments Against Banning Commercial Surrogacy:\n1. May push practice underground with less regulation\n2. Limits reproductive choices for intended parents\n3. Can reduce economic opportunities for surrogates\n4. Might not address root causes of exploitation\n5. Could disproportionately impact lower-income women\n\nAlternative Approaches:\n1. Strong legal regulations\n2. Comprehensive medical and psychological screening\n3. Fair compensation structures\n4. Mandatory health insurance for surrogates\n5. Informed consent protocols\n6. Transparent contractual agreements\n7. International regulatory frameworks\n\nPotential Best Practice:\n- Regulated commercial surrogacy with:\n- Strict legal protections\n- Comprehensive medical guidelines\n- Fair compensation\n- Mandatory psychological support\n- Informed consent mechanisms\n\nThe solution likely requires nuanced, context-specific approaches rather than absolute prohibition.",
